Quality

First of all, what about quality of those red wines Also, quality is a numeric, we will add it as a factor.

It looks like a normal distribution. Notes are out of 10. Most of the wines are around 5/6.

Alcohol

Much more disparate but we have a nice peak around 9.5% by volume. All in all it still looks like a normal distribution.

Residual Sugar

Residual sugar is the amount of sugar remaining after fermentation.

X scale is in log10. We have the same type of distribution but a long tail. Peaks is around 2.5g / dm^3 and data seems to go all the way up until 15g / dm^3. Lets look at the summary.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   0.900   1.900   2.200   2.539   2.600  15.500

Max is at 15 while the 3rd quartile is at 2.6 and the median at 2.2. So those are quite special wines or there is some error in the data.

Chlorides

Chlorides is salt. I woud consider not a great taste in wine.

We have a normal distribution once the x axis is transformed using a log10 function. Like residual.sugar, we have a longtail of data.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
## 0.01200 0.07000 0.07900 0.08747 0.09000 0.61100

The unit is the same as the residual.sugar but the number are way lower. Median is at 0.079g / dm^3. The max is more than 7 time higher.

Citric acid

In small quantities, citric acid can add freshness and pops to wine.

Looking at citric.acid with a log10 scale, we have again a normal distribution.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   0.000   0.090   0.260   0.271   0.420   1.000

Once again we have a median at 0.26 g/dm^3 whereas the max is at 1 and the min is at 0.

pH

pH scale from 0 (very acid) to 14 (very basic). Most wines are between 3 and 4.

The pH is normally distributed with a peak without the need for a log scale. We can see that the data is quite disperse but that as the description says, most of the data points are between 3 and 4.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   2.740   3.210   3.310   3.311   3.400   4.010

The min and max are once again quite far apart from the median and the 1st and 3rd quartiles respectively.

Volatile acidity

Volatile acidity is the amoutn acetic acid in wine. At high concentration it gives an unpleasant vinegar taste which, I think, is what a low quality wine taste like.

Still a long tail in the data with a peak around 0.6 g / dm^3 of acetic acid.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.1200  0.3900  0.5200  0.5278  0.6400  1.5800

The max is really out of range of the other data points. Median is at 0.52 g / dm^3 of acetic acid and the mean is quite similar ar 0.5278 g / dm^3 of acetic acid.

Total Sulfur Dioxide

Total sulfur dioxide is the sum of free (to oxidation of wine) and bound forms of sulfur. At high concentration is can influence taste.

The x axis is transformed using log10. We have several bumps but overall a normal distribution. Some data points seem to be isolated. Lets look at the variable summary.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    6.00   22.00   38.00   46.47   62.00  289.00

The max is really too high compared to the median and the 3rd quartile. It is an error in data reporting/recording I think.

My main line of inquiries will be the relation between all variables to quality.

Bivariate analysis

Alcohol and quality

Does alcohol level affects the quality?

## [1] 0.4761663

There is a medium correlation (around 0.48) between quality and alcohol, the graph shows that the higher the quality, the higher the alcohol. This is especially true for the higher end wines.

Acidity variables

We have 3 types of acidity listed:

  • Fixed acidity: most acids involved with wine or fixed or nonvolatile (do not evaporate readily)
  • Volatile acidity: the amount of acetic acid in wine, which at too high of levels can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar tast
  • Citric acid: found in small quantities, citric acid can add freshness and flavor to wines

They should all relate to the ph I think.

## [1] -0.6829782
## [1] 0.2349373
## [1] -0.5419041

So Fixed acidity and citric acid correlate quite strongly with the pH (around -0.68 and -0.54 respectively), but not the volatile acidity (around 0.23).

Volatile acidity and pH are not related. Even for high quality wines, the pH seems to vary greatly. This confirms the low correlation previously found.

Quality and pH

Lets get a closer look between those pH and quality now.

The higher the quality, the lower the pH it seems.

## [1] -0.05773139

The correlation coefficient between the two is very low at -0.06. So the first impression of the plot is not validated by the number in fact.

## [1] 0.1240516

The vinegar taste brought by volatile acidity is really hurting the quality.

Final Plots and Summary

First of all, there are outliers in the dataset. I tried to remove them when their value seemed to really be out of range. But it might also underlines the diversity of wines. As I am not sure, the following graphs are based on the whole dataset. All in all, there is not some really strong correlations between quality and the other variables presented here. But I could understood some relationships regarding tastes:

Vinegar taste is not really looked for

The density were scaled so that the low counts of the extreme quality do affect the overall distribution. As the quality of the wines get higher, the volatile acidity is getting lower. The correlation is quite strong at -0.391. The negative sign signifies that the higher the volatile acidity (and hence the vinegar taste) the lower the quality. It is not always true. This is kind of what we can expect. When you buy cheap wine (which is not always, but most of the time of lower quality) it has most of the time a pugent smell and taste, like vinegar.

But citric acid is the other way around

This kind of acid add freshness and flavor. It is confirmed by the boxplot: lower quality wines have less citric acid in general than their higher contourparts. The correlation coefficient is at 0.226. We can group quality into 3 supra group:

  1. Quality 3 & 4: low citric acid median at 0.08
  2. Quality 5 & 6: median around 0.24
  3. Quality 7 & 8: median around 0.4

Get high alcohol level and high sulphates for better wines

This graph shows smoothers of alcohol by sulphates for all quality. Quality and alcohol have a strong correlation at 0.476. The correlation between quality and sulphates is weaker at 0.251 but still present.
The low quality (3) wines vary a lot but the overal trend is that they are high in alcohol with low sulphates and the alcohol level decreases as the sulphates level increases. Qualities 4 to 7 are flat overall and the only differences come from the alcohol level.
Quality 8 wines are peculiar in that they are grouped in the top right corner. The relationship is not flat like the other quality (except 3) but those wines have more alcohol and more sulphates.

Reflection

I started the analysis by looking at the data overal. Some data points seemed really far out and during the analysis, I removed some of them. But I decided to keep them in the end as wine tastes can vary greatly.
Looking at the different variables, I decidied to investigate what made a wine good. I started by looking at the main things that could affect taste: alcohol, chlorides, residual.sugar and pH. My first finding was really about alcohol and quality.
I then moved to multivariables analyses by combining alcohol with chlorides and residual.sugar. The overall trends by quality looked quite similar so I tried to plot chlorides with residual.sugar. But the results was not what I was expecting. Thinking that another factor might be related with those two, I went through the the acidity variables and the quality to select volatile.acidity and citric.acidity and plot them with chlorides and residual.sugar. The plots seemed to give something for citric.acid byt I was overreading it, the correlation is low. I did the same exercice for the rest of the variables.
I get all in all several variables correlating with quality: * Alcohol * Volatile acidity (negative correlation) * Citric acid * Sulphates I was looking for some more adavanced relations between the variables but was not able to find them. I am especially surprised that residual.sugar and chlorides does not affect quality more.
The limits of the dataset are really the lack of points on the lower and higher quality wines. Futhermore, the source of the quality is unknown, is it from a professionnal? A store? And we have to keep in mind that taste is a really cultural thing (see the indian food analysis) and a good wine for someone might not be for another. Last but not least, we do not have the age of the wine. In France, one of the first thing we check for a wine is its age because common knowledge dictates that an older wine is better than a younger one (for normal year). I would have love to validate or discard this coutume. Another thing that I would like is to get the name of the wines so that I can get their prices and see if how they relate to quality.
